    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1924-07-26T15:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1924-07-26T15:00:00-05:00" n="451"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d451">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">124.93/76a: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Chargé in Japan</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Caffery</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1924-07-26T16:00:00-04:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">July 26, 1924—4 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>130. Embassy at London is being instructed<note n="96" xml:id="d451fn96">Telegram
                        no. 236, July 26, 1 p.m., to the Ambassador in Great Britain not
                        printed.</note> to discuss with Foreign Office your telegrams 186, July 16,
                    6 p.m., 192, July 22. 5 p.m., and 200, July 26, 10 a.m.,<note n="97"
                        xml:id="d451fn97">Telegram no. 200 from the Chargé in Japan not
                        printed.</note> and Department’s 126, July 18, 6 p.m., and inquire whether
                    Shidehara’s suggestion of July 22 has also been conveyed to the British
                    Government, and if so what is its disposition <pb facs="0587" n="473"
                        xml:id="pg_473"/> thereto. London has further been informed that the
                    Department would not be averse from acting concurrently with the British, French
                    and Japanese Governments in communicating to the Chinese Foreign Office an
                    unreadiness to make the proposed change in the missions at Peking while disunion
                    and disorder prevail in China and while the rights of foreign nationals continue
                    to be so inadequately safeguarded as at present.</p>
                <p>The Department assumes that your Embassy and Peking Legation are making full
                    exchange of reports in this matter.</p>
                <p>Repeat to Peking as No. 172.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Grew</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
